VALUES
(41, 12, 2, 15, 9, 11, 11, NULL, 'Connection of Servants and Land', 'This connection highlights the theme of servants sent to address the state of the land. In Mark, the servant is sent to receive fruit, while in Ezra, the land is described as unclean due to the actions of its people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 19, 1, 3, 3, 'fruit of the vineyard', 'Fruitfulness in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of fruitfulness in both passages. Mark 12:2 speaks of receiving fruit from the vineyard, while Psalms 1:3 describes a tree that brings forth fruit in its season.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 2, 24, 25, 4, 5, 'sent to the husbandmen a servant', 'Servants Sent by God', 'This connection highlights the theme of God sending servants to His people. Both passages emphasize the role of servants, whether prophets or a servant to the husbandmen, in conveying God''s message and expectations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 14, 36, 16, 16, 'beat him, and sent him away empty', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of God''s messengers. In Mark, the servant is beaten and sent away, paralleling the mocking and misuse of prophets in 2 Chronicles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 16, 9, 26, 26, 'beat him, and sent him away empty', 'Rejection of Prophets Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection and mistreatment of God''s messengers. In Mark, the beating and sending away of the servant parallels the slaying of prophets in Nehemiah, highlighting a consistent theme of disobedience and rebellion against divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 24, 26, 20, 24, 'beat him, and sent him away empty', 'Violence Against Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the violent rejection of prophets. In Mark, the servant is beaten and sent away empty, paralleling Urijah''s fate of being sought out and killed by Jehoiakim for his prophetic words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 24, 29, 26, 26, 'sent him away empty', 'Rejection of Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by those claiming to speak for God. Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of individuals who are seen as prophets or messengers, with Mark 12:3 illustrating physical violence and Jeremiah 29:26 addressing imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 44, 7, 52, 52, 'sent him away empty', 'Persecution of Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the violence inflicted upon those who proclaim God''s message, culminating in the betrayal and murder of Jesus, the Just One.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 52, 2, 15, 15, 'sent him away empty', 'Persecution of Prophets and Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution found in both passages. Mark 12:3 describes the mistreatment of a servant, while 1 Thessalonians 2:15 explicitly mentions the killing of Jesus and the persecution of prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 3, 58, 11, 36, 37, 'beat him, and sent him away empty', 'Suffering and Rejection Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of suffering and rejection faced by individuals. In Mark, the character is beaten and sent away empty, while Hebrews describes others enduring cruel mockings and various forms of torment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 16, 9, 30, 30, 'killing some', 'God''s Forbearance and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize God''s patience and the rejection of His messengers. In Mark, the killing of prophets reflects the refusal to heed God''s warnings, similar to Nehemiah''s account of the people ignoring the prophets sent to them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 24, 7, 25, 28, 'killing some', 'Rejection of Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection and violence against God''s messengers. Mark 12:5 reflects the killing of prophets, paralleling Jeremiah 7:25-28''s depiction of the people''s refusal to heed prophetic warnings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 40, 5, 12, 12, 'killing some', 'Persecution of Prophets Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by prophets. Both passages emphasize the suffering of those who deliver God''s message, with Mark noting the killing of messengers and Matthew encouraging rejoicing for enduring similar treatment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 40, 21, 35, 36, 'beating some, and killing some', 'Servants Sent and Abused', 'Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of servants sent by the owner. They describe similar actions of beating and killing, illustrating a consistent theme of rejection and violence against the messengers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 41, 9, 13, 13, 'killing some', 'Connection of Suffering Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering of prophets. In Mark 12:5, the killing of messengers parallels the treatment of Elijah in Mark 9:13.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 42, 6, 22, 23, 'killing some', 'Connection of Prophetic Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering of prophets and the rejection they face. Mark 12:5 describes the killing of messengers, while Luke 6:22-23 speaks of hatred and reproach towards those who follow the Son of man, paralleling the treatment of prophets.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 5, 42, 6, 36, 36, NULL, 'Mercy and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the violent rejection of messengers in Mark and the call for mercy in Luke. Both passages emphasize the need for compassion despite the harsh treatment of others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 40, 3, 17, 17, 'his wellbeloved', 'Connection of Beloved Son', 'This connection highlights the theme of the beloved son in both passages. Mark 12:6 refers to the son as ''his wellbeloved,'' while Matthew 3:17 identifies Jesus as ''my beloved Son.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 58, 1, 1, 2, 'my son', 'Connection of God''s Son', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s Son being sent to humanity. Both passages emphasize the significance of the Son, with Mark noting the sending of the beloved Son and Hebrews declaring that God has spoken through His Son.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 43, 1, 34, 34, 'my son', 'Connection of the Son of God', 'This connection highlights the identity of the son mentioned in Mark 12:6 as the well-beloved son, which parallels John 1:34''s declaration of Jesus as the Son of God. Both passages emphasize the significance of the son in relation to God and the expectation of reverence.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 1, 22, 2, 2, 'his wellbeloved', 'Connection of Beloved Sons', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of a beloved son being sent or offered. In Mark, the son is sent to be reverenced, while in Genesis, the son is commanded to be offered as a sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 1, 22, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Beloved Sons', 'This connection highlights the theme of beloved sons being sent or offered. In Mark, the son is sent with the expectation of reverence, while in Genesis, the son is not withheld, demonstrating a profound relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 19, 2, 12, 12, 'my son', 'Connection Between Son References', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the Son. Mark 12:6 mentions the son being sent, while Psalms 2:12 urges reverence for the Son to avoid wrath.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 6, 23, 42, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Beloved Son and Servant', 'This connection highlights the theme of a beloved figure sent by God. Both passages emphasize the special status of the son and servant, indicating divine approval and purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 7, 1, 3, 15, 15, 'the heir; come, let us kill him', 'Conflict Over Inheritance', 'This connection highlights the theme of conflict over inheritance and authority. In Mark, the husbandmen seek to kill the heir to claim the inheritance, while Genesis introduces enmity between the seed of the woman and the serpent, indicating a struggle for dominion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 7, 1, 37, 20, 20, 'let us kill him', 'Murder of the Heir', 'Both passages emphasize the plot to kill a favored son, highlighting betrayal and the desire for inheritance. This connection illustrates a recurring theme of jealousy and treachery in familial relationships.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 7, 19, 2, 2, 3, 'let us kill him', 'Rejection of Authority Theme', 'Both passages emphasize a rebellion against authority. In Mark, the husbandmen plot to kill the heir, while in Psalms, rulers conspire against the Lord and His anointed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 12, 7, 19, 22, 12, 15, NULL, 'Connection of Rejection and Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection leading to suffering. In Mark, the husbandmen plot to kill the heir, while in Psalms, the speaker describes being surrounded and beset, indicating a deep sense of distress and abandonment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
